On the night of Pearl Harbour,

435
00:33:02,480 --> 00:33:05,399
one man had been happy -
Winston Churchill.

436
00:33:05,483 --> 00:33:08,694
For now he knew Britain was saved.

437
00:33:08,778 --> 00:33:11,238
A few days later
he journeyed to Washington

438
00:33:11,322 --> 00:33:13,782
to make sure the war
was going to be fought

439
00:33:13,866 --> 00:33:17,953
on the British plan of Europe first
and the Pacific second,

440
00:33:18,037 --> 00:33:21,581
and to cement
the new Anglo-American alliance.

441
00:33:21,666 --> 00:33:25,419
What kind of a people
do they think we are?

442
00:33:25,503 --> 00:33:28,463
ls it possible they do not realise

443
00:33:28,548 --> 00:33:33,135
that we shall never cease
to persevere against them

444
00:33:33,219 --> 00:33:35,887
until they have been taught a lesson

445
00:33:35,972 --> 00:33:39,224
which they and the world
will never forget.

446
00:33:47,608 --> 00:33:52,195
(narrator) Time, Churchill knew,
was on the Allies' side.

447
00:33:52,280 --> 00:33:58,035
With America's industrial might
behind them, they could not lose.

448
00:33:59,287 --> 00:34:00,454
(shouts order)

449
00:34:07,879 --> 00:34:11,798
1942 began badly
for the Americans in the Pacific.

450
00:34:11,883 --> 00:34:17,846
Manila, capital of the Philippines,
fell to the Japanese on January 1 .

451
00:34:20,391 --> 00:34:23,060
The Japanese
pushed the American forces

452
00:34:23,144 --> 00:34:25,979
back into the narrow peninsular
of Bataan.

453
00:34:33,196 --> 00:34:35,280
The American plan was to hold out there

454
00:34:35,364 --> 00:34:38,909
for six months or so,
until reinforcements came.

455
00:34:38,993 --> 00:34:41,787
But the reinforcements never did come,

456
00:34:41,871 --> 00:34:46,625
and nor had Bataan
been really prepared for a siege.

457
00:35:09,982 --> 00:35:13,860
The American troops besieged at Bataan
had no air support,

458
00:35:13,945 --> 00:35:18,240
were short of medical supplies
and their morale was poor.

459
00:35:18,324 --> 00:35:21,660
Even their commander-in-chief,
General MacArthur,

460
00:35:21,786 --> 00:35:24,579
had leff them for safer shores.

461
00:35:26,332 --> 00:35:30,669
Their bitter ballad:
"We are the battling bastards of Bataan

462
00:35:30,753 --> 00:35:33,713
No mama, no papa, no Uncle Sam

463
00:35:33,798 --> 00:35:37,092
No aunts, no uncles,
no cousins, no nieces,

464
00:35:37,176 --> 00:35:40,220
No pills, no planes or artillery pieces

465
00:35:40,304 --> 00:35:43,348
And nobody gives a goddamn."

466
00:35:45,560 --> 00:35:48,353
Cock-a-hoop with the ease
of their victory so far,

467
00:35:48,437 --> 00:35:54,901
the Japanese called on the Americans
beleaguered in Bataan to surrender.

468
00:35:54,986 --> 00:36:01,533
The voice of the Philippines calling
the attention of everyone everywhere.

469
00:36:02,326 --> 00:36:09,708
Everyone everywhere, Filipinos
and Americans all over the country...

470
00:36:12,211 --> 00:36:14,963
(narrator) They tried leaflets too...

471
00:36:17,633 --> 00:36:23,763
aimed mostly at the Filipino soldiers
among the American forces.

472
00:36:24,807 --> 00:36:28,935
The Japanese closed in for the kill.

473
00:37:07,892 --> 00:37:09,434
ln early May, 1942,

474
00:37:09,518 --> 00:37:13,396
the American commander in the
Philippines, General Wainwright,

475
00:37:13,481 --> 00:37:18,109
bowed to the inevitable and surrendered
the remainder of his forces.

476
00:37:18,194 --> 00:37:23,198
(mterpreter) l've decided to accept,
in the name of humanity,

477
00:37:23,282 --> 00:37:31,164
the formal surrender of all American
and Philippine army troops

478
00:37:31,249 --> 00:37:33,375
in the Philippine lslands.

479
00:37:33,459 --> 00:37:41,466
You will - repeat, will - surrender all
troops to the proper Japanese officer.

480
00:37:42,551 --> 00:37:45,679
(narrator)
80,000 Americans surrendered,

481
00:37:45,763 --> 00:37:51,184
the largest mass capitulation
in American military history.

482
00:37:51,269 --> 00:37:54,312
The Japanese made the Americans
march in the blazing sun

483
00:37:54,397 --> 00:37:58,191
to prison camps
100 or so miles from Bataan.

484
00:37:58,276 --> 00:38:03,446
Deprived of water and medicine,
starVed and brutally beaten,

485
00:38:03,531 --> 00:38:07,117
some 10,000 soldiers
died along the way -

486
00:38:07,201 --> 00:38:11,246
more than had been killed
in the actual fighting for Bataan.

487
00:38:21,340 --> 00:38:25,969
By that spring of 1942, the Japanese
conquests were at their peak.

488
00:38:26,053 --> 00:38:30,348
Surely the British and Americans would
now want to make peace, argued Tokyo -

489
00:38:30,433 --> 00:38:34,686
a peace that would allow the Japanese
to retain their conquests.

490
00:38:34,770 --> 00:38:39,566
But already bold steps were being taken
to strike back at the Japanese

491
00:38:39,650 --> 00:38:43,486
here in the heart of their empire,
Tokyo.

492
00:38:43,571 --> 00:38:47,073
l was on this cruiser
called the Northampton

493
00:38:47,158 --> 00:38:52,454
and we were several days out at sea
when we saw the Hornet coming up.

494
00:38:52,580 --> 00:38:55,957
And the Hornet
had very unusual planes on deck -

495
00:38:56,042 --> 00:38:58,168
you could see them from a long way.

496
00:38:58,252 --> 00:39:02,589
They were large
land-based planes - B-25s.

497
00:39:04,008 --> 00:39:11,681
(man) We had only one real worry -
that would have been a dead calm.

498
00:39:11,766 --> 00:39:13,308
Under those conditions,

499
00:39:13,392 --> 00:39:16,978
taking off the carrier deck
with the heavy loads that we had

500
00:39:17,104 --> 00:39:19,356
would have been at best precarious.

501
00:39:19,440 --> 00:39:21,941
The worst thing we thought might happen

502
00:39:22,026 --> 00:39:25,445
would be a completely alerted Japan
waiting for us.

503
00:39:25,529 --> 00:39:31,076
What did happen was that
the morning just before take-off

504
00:39:31,160 --> 00:39:34,079
we encountered
two Japanese fishing boats.

505
00:39:34,163 --> 00:39:39,501
They spotted our task force,
sent a message to the mainland,

506
00:39:39,585 --> 00:39:42,879
but, unfortunately for the Japanese,

507
00:39:42,963 --> 00:39:47,092
were sunk
before they could repeat the message.

508
00:39:50,679 --> 00:39:54,391
So we achieved almost complete surprise.

509
00:40:16,288 --> 00:40:21,376
The actual amount of damage done
was minimal.

510
00:40:21,460 --> 00:40:26,256
We were 16 aeroplanes,
each with one ton of bombs.

511
00:40:26,340 --> 00:40:31,594
ln the later stages of World War ll,
the 20th Air Force under LeMay

512
00:40:31,679 --> 00:40:36,266
was sending out 500 aeroplanes,
each with 10 tons of bombs.

513
00:40:36,392 --> 00:40:40,728
So we dropped 16
against a later raid of 5,000,

514
00:40:40,813 --> 00:40:43,982
so the damage was not at all great.

515
00:40:44,066 --> 00:40:46,860
However, it did have some advantages.

516
00:40:46,944 --> 00:40:50,947
One, we had had
nothing but bad news at home,

517
00:40:51,031 --> 00:40:53,575
so it was the first good news
our folks got

518
00:40:53,659 --> 00:40:57,162
and it was appreciated as good news.

519
00:40:57,246 --> 00:41:00,707
lt caused the Japanese
to question their warlords,

520
00:41:00,791 --> 00:41:04,627
who had informed them
that Japan would never be attacked.

521
00:41:07,548 --> 00:41:12,594
(narrator) The Doolittle raid stung
Japan's leaders and made them careless.

522
00:41:13,179 --> 00:41:14,387
Ever since Pearl Harbour,

523
00:41:14,472 --> 00:41:18,391
Japan's navy had sought a decisive
battle with America's navy,

524
00:41:18,476 --> 00:41:24,272
a battle that would decide
once and for all mastery of the Pacific.

525
00:41:31,614 --> 00:41:34,866
ln early June, 1942,
the Japanese carriers

526
00:41:34,950 --> 00:41:38,161
rendezvous'd close to Midway lsland,

527
00:41:38,245 --> 00:41:41,956
some 1300 miles northwest of Hawaii.

528
00:41:56,931 --> 00:41:59,015
(speaking Japanese)

529
00:41:59,934 --> 00:42:02,936
(translator)
We had ceased to be as wary as before.

530
00:42:03,020 --> 00:42:06,898
The Americans knew in advance
that we would attack Midway.

531
00:42:06,982 --> 00:42:10,151
They were waiting for us
and we walked into their trap.

532
00:43:44,496 --> 00:43:46,748
(narrator)
But while the Japanese navy's

533
00:43:46,874 --> 00:43:49,167
attention was focused on Midway lsland,

534
00:43:49,251 --> 00:43:51,210
the American navy were preparing

535
00:43:51,295 --> 00:43:53,713
to strike back
at the Japanese carrier fleet.

536
00:43:53,797 --> 00:43:57,175
(man) We had a wonderful advantage -
we were breaking their code

537
00:43:57,259 --> 00:43:58,718
and they didn't know it.

538
00:43:58,802 --> 00:44:01,804
So we had some idea
what was going to happen there.

539
00:44:01,889 --> 00:44:03,765
We were on the scene

540
00:44:03,849 --> 00:44:09,103
with the carrier force in the right spot
to meet them.

541
00:45:14,044 --> 00:45:17,755
(narrator) Midway, one of the greatest
sea battles of all time,

542
00:45:17,840 --> 00:45:21,676
meant the US regained
naval control of the Pacific

543
00:45:21,760 --> 00:45:26,806
and was the end of Japan's hope
of any further conquests.

544
00:45:28,267 --> 00:45:29,851
The four Japanese carriers

545
00:45:29,935 --> 00:45:33,396
that had launched the raid
on Pearl Harbour six months before

546
00:45:33,480 --> 00:45:37,150
were destroyed by planes
from the very American carriers

547
00:45:37,234 --> 00:45:42,029
that had been at sea
and escaped destruction that day.

548
00:45:46,118 --> 00:45:50,455
The Battle of Midway doomed Japan.

549
00:45:50,539 --> 00:45:56,085
The Midway battle was, many people say,
the turning point of the Pacific war -

550
00:45:56,170 --> 00:46:01,466
that is, the turning point
from complete retreat on our part,

551
00:46:01,550 --> 00:46:06,804
or at least an attempt
to establish a stalemate, and offensive.

552
00:46:06,889 --> 00:46:12,602
(narrator) Turning point
not just at sea, but on land too.

553
00:46:14,730 --> 00:46:17,690
The island of Guadalcanal
in the Solomons,

554
00:46:17,775 --> 00:46:22,403
the southernmost limit
of the Japanese conquests.

555
00:46:27,159 --> 00:46:30,036
ln August 1942, the Allies returned.

556
00:46:30,120 --> 00:46:33,956
For the Americans,
it was their first invasion of the war.

557
00:46:34,041 --> 00:46:38,920
(man) We had such a tiny fraction
of America's force and money -

558
00:46:39,004 --> 00:46:41,464
resources and manpower resources.

559
00:46:41,548 --> 00:46:44,217
90% went to Europe.

560
00:46:44,301 --> 00:46:48,846
We had such a tiny little thread
of existence down there.

561
00:46:48,931 --> 00:46:51,432
lt was our first offensive
in the Pacific

562
00:46:51,517 --> 00:46:55,269
and we went in with only one division.

563
00:47:14,873 --> 00:47:19,460
The Japanese were tough fighters
and they never would give up.

564
00:47:19,545 --> 00:47:22,463
We had isolated a Japanese regiment

565
00:47:22,548 --> 00:47:25,925
in what was known as
the Gifu strongpoint,

566
00:47:26,009 --> 00:47:29,262
and they fought until
we actually had to annihilate them.

567
00:47:29,346 --> 00:47:33,140
We used loudspeakers
affer we had surrounded them

568
00:47:33,225 --> 00:47:36,727
and tried to persuade them to surrender,
but they wouldn't.

569
00:47:36,812 --> 00:47:43,776
Japanese shouldn't have made
such a great effort in Guadalcanal.

570
00:47:43,861 --> 00:47:46,612
They could have saved their strength.

571
00:47:47,990 --> 00:47:50,116
(flies buzzing)

572
00:48:27,279 --> 00:48:31,616
(narrator) At long last the tide had
turned for the Allies in the Pacific.

573
00:48:31,700 --> 00:48:34,869
But it was still as yet only a sideshow.

574
00:48:34,953 --> 00:48:38,539
The main energies
were being reserVed for Europe.

575
00:48:38,624 --> 00:48:40,458
lt was really a little odd

576
00:48:40,542 --> 00:48:44,253
to the Americans in the general public
at that time

577
00:48:44,338 --> 00:48:48,299
that we were spending
so little effort in the Pacific.

578
00:48:48,383 --> 00:48:52,470
President Roosevelt made up his mind
that the defeat of Hitler

579
00:48:52,554 --> 00:48:57,683
was by far the most important
to achieve first -

580
00:48:57,768 --> 00:49:00,686
he was the most dangerous
of the enemies.

581
00:49:00,771 --> 00:49:02,438
And he was very skilful

582
00:49:02,564 --> 00:49:07,276
in keeping American public opinion
directed towards Europe,

583
00:49:07,361 --> 00:49:09,862
although we did have
a very major operation

584
00:49:09,947 --> 00:49:12,406
in Japan
and a very successful operation,

585
00:49:12,491 --> 00:49:15,034
affer we recovered
from the tremendous blow

586
00:49:15,118 --> 00:49:18,454
of the loss of a substantial
part of our navy at Pearl Harbour.

587
00:49:18,538 --> 00:49:25,711
l think that generally public opinion
had the feeling, as we say in baseball,

588
00:49:25,796 --> 00:49:28,506
the big league was in Europe

589
00:49:28,590 --> 00:49:33,344
and in the United Kingdom -
l include that in Western Europe.

590
00:49:33,428 --> 00:49:36,263
The decision was made early

591
00:49:36,348 --> 00:49:41,560
that Europe came first -
and it was a wise decision -

592
00:49:41,645 --> 00:49:43,062
in spite of the fact

593
00:49:43,146 --> 00:49:47,984
we got the devil knocked out of us
in the Pacific for a long time.

594
00:49:48,068 --> 00:49:52,863
That was the right decision
and l think everybody recognised it.

595
00:49:52,948 --> 00:49:56,158
Now, of course, the navy protested

596
00:49:56,243 --> 00:50:00,621
at being leff
way underpowered in the Pacific.

597
00:50:00,706 --> 00:50:07,878
And it did put us up to
very heavy casualties and all of that.

598
00:50:07,963 --> 00:50:13,467
But l think the country in general
agreed with the decision

599
00:50:13,552 --> 00:50:17,263
that the real threat was in Europe.

600
00:50:17,347 --> 00:50:20,349
We could take care of the Japs
in our own good time,

601
00:50:20,434 --> 00:50:26,480
but the real thing that had to be met
was on the Continent.

602
00:50:37,534 --> 00:50:41,078
♪ This is the army, Mr Jones

603
00:50:41,163 --> 00:50:45,458
♪ No private rooms or telephones

604
00:50:45,542 --> 00:50:48,919
♪ You had your breakfast in bed before

605
00:50:49,004 --> 00:50:53,090
♪ But you won't have it there any more

606
00:50:53,175 --> 00:50:55,009
Here we teach you how to kill:

607
00:50:55,093 --> 00:50:58,345
get the opponent on the ground
as quick as possible

608
00:50:58,430 --> 00:51:01,140
and snuff out his life
by kicking with both feet,

609
00:51:01,224 --> 00:51:02,933
one foot, the flat of the hand,

610
00:51:03,018 --> 00:51:06,103
a rabbit punch,
gouging the eyes out, ripping the mouth.

611
00:51:06,188 --> 00:51:08,564
The gentle art of killing a man

612
00:51:08,690 --> 00:51:13,027
is to get him on the ground
and kick in this manner. See?

613
00:51:17,824 --> 00:51:20,534
Come on, all of you do that.
Come on.

614
00:51:21,661 --> 00:51:25,331
♪ Do what the buglers command

615
00:51:25,415 --> 00:51:29,543
♪ They're in the army and not in a band

616
00:51:29,628 --> 00:51:33,798
♪ This is the army, Mr Brown

617
00:51:33,882 --> 00:51:37,343
♪ You and your baby went to town

618
00:51:37,427 --> 00:51:40,846
♪ She had you worried,
but this is war

619
00:51:40,931 --> 00:51:44,767
♪ And she won't worry you any more

620
00:51:44,851 --> 00:51:48,938
♪ Mr Jones, Mr Green

621
00:51:49,022 --> 00:51:50,940
♪ Mr Brown...

622
00:51:51,024 --> 00:51:57,321
Mr Churchill
did have a real antipathy, l think,

623
00:51:57,405 --> 00:52:04,620
toward getting ashore what he would call
prematurely onto the European continent.

624
00:52:04,704 --> 00:52:06,956
He had very vivid memories

625
00:52:07,040 --> 00:52:11,669
of the sacrifice
of a British generation in World War l.

626
00:52:11,753 --> 00:52:15,798
Passchendaele and the Somme -
they were always nightmares to him.

627
00:52:15,924 --> 00:52:17,842
Affer all this passion

628
00:52:17,968 --> 00:52:20,928
that had been aroused
as a result of Pearl Harbour

629
00:52:21,054 --> 00:52:24,807
and our being in the war, marching
and counter-marching and training,

630
00:52:24,891 --> 00:52:26,976
we just had to get ashore someplace.

631
00:52:27,060 --> 00:52:28,811
ln view of the British attitude,

632
00:52:28,895 --> 00:52:33,440
which felt we weren't prepared
to go into the main theatre,

633
00:52:33,525 --> 00:52:36,944
we sniffed around for another spot
to express our strength

634
00:52:37,028 --> 00:52:38,863
and it turned out it was Africa.

635
00:52:38,947 --> 00:52:43,492
♪ Over there

636
00:52:43,577 --> 00:52:45,744
♪ Send the word, send the word

637
00:52:45,829 --> 00:52:47,955
♪ Over there

638
00:52:48,039 --> 00:52:50,499
♪ That the Yanks are coming

639
00:52:50,584 --> 00:52:53,002
♪ The Yanks are coming

640
00:52:53,086 --> 00:52:56,463
♪ The drums rum-tumming everywhere

641
00:52:57,048 --> 00:52:59,133
♪ So prepare

642
00:52:59,217 --> 00:53:01,552
♪ Say a prayer

643
00:53:01,636 --> 00:53:03,679
♪ Send the word, send the word

644
00:53:03,763 --> 00:53:05,931
♪ To beware

645
00:53:06,016 --> 00:53:08,100
♪ We'll be over

646
00:53:08,185 --> 00:53:10,477
♪ We're coming over

647
00:53:10,562 --> 00:53:24,241
♪ And we won't come back
till it's over over there

648
00:53:26,703 --> 00:53:29,455
(narrator) November, 1942.

649
00:53:29,539 --> 00:53:32,333
600 ships, loaded with men and material,

650
00:53:32,459 --> 00:53:36,212
set sail for North Africa -
Operation Torch.

651
00:53:36,296 --> 00:53:41,342
Said Roosevelt, when he heard the news,
"At last we're on our way."
